So, this is to do with inheritance :)

We haven't learned about this yet in class, but basically, inheritance is a way of doing what's known as "polymorphism" - doing the same thing on different types. A good example of this polymorphism is the `toString` function.

Every class type in Java has its own toString function; the default just prints that weird hash thing. However, if you write the method in your own class, then it'll override that default. String's `+` operator takes advantage of this - if you do:

String s = "Hello " + someObject;

Then Java will turn this into

String s = "Hello " + someObject.toString();

So if we overload `toString` on the Circle type, then `"Circle1=" + circle1` will call `circle1.toString()` to get the representation of that circle as a string.

Note: the rest of this post is just informational, if you're curious. You don't have to know this, and if you're a little confused, that's fine :)

If you wanted to take advantage of this for yourself, you'd write some base class (for `toString`, that base class is `Object`, which is the base class of all class types):

class Shape {    virtual public float area() {        return 0;    }}

And then you could write your own classes which "inherit" from Shape:

class Circle extends Shape {    float radius;    Circle(float radius) {        this.radius = radius;    }    virtual public float area() {        return Math.PI * radius * radius;    }}class Rectangle extends Shape {
    float base;    float height;
    Rectangle(float base, float height) {        this.base = base;        this.height = height;    }
    virtual public float area() {
        return base * height;
    }
}

And then you can write methods which can take any kind of shape:

class Main {    public static void main(String[] args) {        printArea(new Circle(1.0)); // 3.1415...        printArea(new Rectangle(5.0, 3.0)); // 15.0    }    private static void printArea(Shape shape) {        System.out.println("This shape has area " + shape.area());    }}

Notes: You shouldn't use inheritance for this, you should use interfaces; this was just a toy example.
